gement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2d5e11b2-f829-5c8a-ba4e-4bd0c552209e","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"4a6cc052-004c-5f0c-83f8-f04899c06292","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"e1ee9217-75fd-57a2-8e67-0f9c468e36c9","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"a6d40f6b-b733-5a56-8b81-ff55062d9bcb","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"b7921f28-c4d4-513c-9424-c072661841bd","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"b8d0a623-b3f6-56ab-8f3b-53e9862e41cf","slug":"recognizing-the-terminal-phase","fullItemName":"Recognizing the terminal phase","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field a82fbf3d-b808-4a90-81c7-d270b8ff0231 --><h3>How to recognize the terminal phase</h3><!-- end field a82fbf3d-b808-4a90-81c7-d270b8ff0231 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 1528a013-436d-4d2d-9703-a6ab0083f057 --><!-- begin field b539ec6f-4ace-4173-887e-69fcfb97930e --><ul><li>It can often be difficult to be certain that a person is dying, but it is essential to recognize the signs of dying in order to appropriately care for people at the end of life.</li><li>The terminal phase may last hours to several days.</li><li>People are likely to be in the terminal phase of their illness when they:<ul><li>Deteriorate day by day or more rapidly.</li><li>Have a reduced mobility and become progressively weak and fatigued without an apparent cause (for example hypercalcaemia).</li><li>Express a realization that they are dying.</li><li>Have reduced cognition, ability to communicate and social withdrawal.</li><li>Have a deterioration in level of consciousness.</li><li>Are delirious, characterized by increased restlessness, confusion, and agitation.</li><li>Are bed-bound.</li><li>Take little food or fluid, and have difficulty taking oral medication.</li><li>Are peripherally cyanosed, have mottled skin and are cold to the touch.</li><li>Have apnoea (whether awake or asleep) or an altered breathing pattern, such as Cheyne-Stokes breathing.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field b539ec6f-4ace-4173-887e-69fcfb97930e --><!-- end item 1528a013-436d-4d2d-9703-a6ab0083f057 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"d4933b0a-8e17-5f33-afbf-3ec66c6fb649","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-5ed","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field e5a70922-99dc-4977-9f11-c5dc155e548a --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field e5a70922-99dc-4977-9f11-c5dc155e548a -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 5eda8eb7-017d-43c5-b177-0269bea18197 --><!-- begin field e2b76ebe-b9f3-4b45-b663-dcdee40b89ac --><ul><li>The definition of the terminal phase in terms of timescale is based on a prospective study of 100 terminally ill cancer patients [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Morita et al, 1998</a>].</li><li>These recommendations are largely based on the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guideline <em>Care of dying adults in the last days of life</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">NICE, 2015</a>]. The basis for the NICE recommendations has been briefly summarized in this section. For detailed information on the evidence NICE used to make these recommendations, see the full <a href=\"https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng31/chapter/Recommendations\" data-hyperlink-id=\"c3fe20ac-56ef-415b-9975-a993004ade36\">NICE guideline.</a></li></ul><!-- end field e2b76ebe-b9f3-4b45-b663-dcdee40b89ac --><!-- end item 5eda8eb7-017d-43c5-b177-0269bea18197 -->","subChapters":[]}]},{"id":"9068fe30-ad9f-50b6-9e2d-1999b2c12425","slug":"oral-care-in-the-terminal-phase","fullItemName":"Oral care in the terminal phase","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field de18375d-577b-4c34-8d2a-f4489da1269d --><h3>How should I manage oral care in the terminal phase?</h3><!-- end field de18375d-577b-4c34-8d2a-f4489da1269d -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e952219b-25a2-4ffd-8007-dd0000563243 --><!-- begin field e9589c3b-782c-4515-b362-288b97251c7c --><ul><li><strong>The management of dry mouth should be included in the person's care plan.</strong></li><li><strong>Consider changing or stopping medications which are causing dry mouth</strong>.</li><li><strong>Carry out mouth care as often as necessary to maintain a clean mouth.</strong><ul><li><strong>In people who are conscious,</strong> the mouth can be moistened every 30 minutes with water from a water spray or dropper, or ice chips can be placed in the mouth.</li><li><strong>In unconscious people,</strong> moisten the mouth at least once an hour with water from a water spray, dropper, or sponge stick or ice chips placed in the mouth.</li><li><strong>To prevent cracking of the lips,</strong> smear petroleum jelly (for example Vaseline<sup>®</sup>) on the lips. However, if a person is on oxygen apply a water-soluble lubricant (for example K-Y Jelly<sup>®</sup>).</li><li><strong>When the weather is dry and hot,</strong> if possible, use a room humidifier or air conditioning.</li><li><strong>Ensure help is offered to clean teeth or dentures.</strong></li><li><strong>Manage pain symptomatically,</strong> using analgesics via a suitable route. Stop treatment of the underlying cause of pain when the burden of treatment outweighs the benefits. See <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/management/oral-pain/\">Scenario: Oral pain </a>.</li><li>See <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/management/prevention/#self-care\">Self-care</a> for further information.</li></ul></li></ul><ul><li><strong>For more information on managing hydration see</strong> <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-general-issues/management/terminal-phase/#care-adjustments-in-the-terminal-phase\">Care adjustments in the terminal phase</a> in <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-general-issues/\">Palliative care - general issues</a>.</li></ul><!-- end field e9589c3b-782c-4515-b362-288b97251c7c --><!-- end item e952219b-25a2-4ffd-8007-dd0000563243 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"b32d9109-436e-5173-b22d-ec8c5c7cdeb0","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-65b","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9ac329e0-3d26-482e-aedc-cb8d93d53fc0 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 9ac329e0-3d26-482e-aedc-cb8d93d53fc0 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 65bec4ba-7911-479f-89ba-290dae84c8b5 --><!-- begin field b779c5ba-4b30-4719-9204-450855ecd11e --><p>The basis for these recommendations is the NICE guideline, <em>Care of dying adults in the last days of life </em>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">NICE, 2015</a>]<em> </em>and expert opinion [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Ellershaw et al, 1995</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-oral/references/\">Twycross et al, 2009</a>].</p><ul><li>People in the last 24–48 hours of life often have difficulty taking food, fluid, or oral medication. Good symptom control may allow the dying person to eat, drink, and talk comfortably. Mouth care can easily be carried out by the family, giving them greater involvement in the care of their dying relative.</li></ul><!-- end field b779c5ba-4b30-4719-9204-450855ecd11e --><!-- end item 65bec4ba-7911-479f-89ba-290dae84c8b5 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}